<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xml:lang="en"><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.3.2">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" hreflang="en"/><updated>2024-05-29T20:40:09-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/feed.xml</id><title type="html">blank</title><subtitle>A simple, whitespace theme for academics. Based on [*folio](https://github.com/bogoli/-folio) design. </subtitle><entry><title type="html">Neural Architecture Search</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/nas/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Neural Architecture Search"/><published>2023-09-26T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-09-26T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/nas</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/nas/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="ml"/><category term="ai"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[This will consist of my notes on Neural Architecture Search (NAS).]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">A Neat Derivative Trick</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/derivative/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="A Neat Derivative Trick"/><published>2023-08-07T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-07T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/derivative</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/derivative/"><![CDATA[<p>Which is larger \(\pi^e\) or \(e^{\pi}\)? Hint: consider \(\log x/x\).</p> <p>Suppose \(\alpha&gt;\beta\). The key observation is if we take the natural logarithm of both sides, then \(\log \alpha &gt; \log \beta\) would imply \(\alpha&gt;\beta\) since the logarithm is montonically increasing (and concave).</p> <p>Hence, let \(y=\frac{\log x}{x}\). Consider the first derivative: \begin{equation} \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{1}{x^2}-\frac{\log}{x^2}=\frac{1-\log x}{x^2}. \end{equation}</p> <p>Note that \(y'(e)=\frac{1-\log e}{e^2}=0\) and \(y'(\pi)=\frac{1-\log \pi}{\pi^2}&lt;0\), as \(\pi &gt; e\). Indeed, \(y'(x)&lt;0\) on \([e,\pi]\). Notice that \(y(x)\) has a maximum at \(x=e\) since \(y'(e)=0\). Thus, \begin{equation} \frac{\log e}{e} &gt; \frac{\log \pi}{\pi}. \end{equation}</p> <p>It follows that \(\pi \log e&gt;e\log \pi\) or \(e^\pi&gt;\pi^e\).</p> <p>One can also use a Taylor series for \(e^x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{x^n}{n!}\), substituting \(x=\frac{\pi}{e}-1\) to see this, albeit less intutivie.</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="derivatives"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[An interesting brainteaser.]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">The Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman Equation</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hjb/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="The Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman Equation"/><published>2023-08-06T08:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T08:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hjb</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hjb/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="stochasticcalculus"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Deriving the Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman Equation]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Deriving Ito’s Formula</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/ito/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Deriving Ito’s Formula"/><published>2023-08-06T08:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T08:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/ito</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/ito/"><![CDATA[<p>It’s been a couple months since I’ve looked into the weeds of stochastic calculus, so I plan to write a series deriving a few rudimentary results. I will follow my notes from Math 236: Stochastic Differential Equations.</p> <p>Let \(\Delta B_1, \Delta B_2,\dots\) be a sequence of i.i.d. Gaussian random variables with zero mean and variance \(\Delta t\).</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="stochasticcalculus"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Deriving Ito's Formula]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Implied Volatility</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/implied_volatility/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Implied Volatility"/><published>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/implied_volatility</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/implied_volatility/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="stochasticcalculus"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Implied Volatility]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">The Kelly Betting Criterion</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/kelly/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="The Kelly Betting Criterion"/><published>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/kelly</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/kelly/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="optimization"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Kelly Betting Criterion]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Black-Scholes and Options Pricing</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/options/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Black-Scholes and Options Pricing"/><published>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/options</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/options/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="stochasticcalculus"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Deriving the Black-Scholes equation]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Linear Regression</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/regression/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Linear Regression"/><published>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/regression</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/regression/"><![CDATA[<p>TBD</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="mathematics"/><category term="statistics"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[Basic statistical properties of linear regression]]></summary></entry><entry><title type="html">The Avellaneda Stoikov Model</title><link href="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hft/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="The Avellaneda Stoikov Model"/><published>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</published><updated>2023-08-06T02:00:00-04:00</updated><id>https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hft</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sergiogcharles.github.io/blog/2023/hft/"><![CDATA[<p>In this post, I will describe an approach to high-frequency trading, whereby we optimize the following objective: \begin{equation} \sup_{\delta_t^a,\delta_t^b}\mathbb{E}[U(W_T)] \end{equation}</p> <p>whereby \(W_t=X_t+Q_tS_t\) is the wealth of the trader, \(X_t\) is the cash, and \(Q_t\) is the quantity of the risky-asset (stock) \(S_t\).</p> <p>TO BE CONTINUED….</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="trading"/><category term="HFT"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[High-frequency trading under the Avellaneda Stoikov model]]></summary></entry></feed>